$$
(10^{10^9} - 1)/9 \equiv 0 \bmod{p}
$$

If $r$ is order of $10$ mod $p$, want
$$
r \equiv 10^9 \bmod{p-1} \; .
$$

We could look at primes of the form $p = k10^9 + 1$
It is easy to find $40$ of these.

We have to consider primes where $(10^{10^9}-1)/9 = 0 \bmod{p}$
and $10^9 \not\equiv 0 \bmod{p-1}$.

What about if $10^{(p-1)/2} = 1 \bmod{p}$.  Then
$$
10^9 = \frac{p-1}{2} \bmod{p-1}
$$
gives
$$
10^9 = \frac{k}{2} (p-1)
$$
and so
$$
\frac{2}{k} 10^9 + 1 = p \; .
$$

In general
$$
10^9 = \frac{p-1}{r} \bmod{p-1}
$$
gives
$$
10^9 = \frac{k}{r} \cdot (p-1)
$$
so
$$
\frac{r}{k} 10^9 + 1 = p \; .
$$
Need $k | 10^9$.

# Note

Let $d$ be a divisor of $10^9$.
Looking for $p = kd + 1$ and $10^d = 1 \bmod{p}$.
At least need $10^d \geq p$.

# Idea

If $10^10 = 1 \bmod{p}$, then $10^{10^9} = (10^{10})^{10^8} = 1 \bmod{p}$.

**Note**

$$
10^{10^9}-1
=
(10^{10^9/2}-1)(10^{10^9/2}-1)
$$
